section.subsection:
Vector Equations


    A vector equation, naturally, is an equation involving vectors.



    Let,

        \vec{a}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} \qquad \vec{a}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} \qquad \vec{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}

    and consider the equation,

        x_1 \vec{a}_1 + x_2 \vec{a}_2 = \vec{b}

    Here, the unknowns are x_1 and x_2. Intuitively, this represents the questions of whether \vec{b} can be written as a linear combination of \vec{a}_1 and \vec{a}_2. In other words, if there exists weights x_1, x_2 such that the linear combination x_1 \vec{a}_1 + x_2 \vec{a}_2 is equal to \vec{b}. Using the properties of vectors, we can combine and simplify the left-hand side,

        x_1 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} + x_2 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ -2x_1 \\ -5x_1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 2x_2 \\ 5x_2 \\ 6x_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix} x_1 + 2x_2 \\ -2x_1 + 5x_2 \\ -5x_1 + 6x_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}

    This vector equation is equivalent to the original equation, but it is in a more convenient form. By the definition of equality for vectors, we know that these two vectors are equal if and only if their corresponding entries are equal. In other words, if x_1, x_2 is a solution to the linear system,

        \begin{array}{rrrr}
        x_1 \amp + 2x_2 \amp = \amp 7 \\
        -2x_1 \amp + 5x_2 \amp = \amp 4 \\
        -5x_1 \amp + 6x_2 \amp = -3
        \end{array}

    Using row reduction,

        \left[\begin{array}{cc|c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 7 \\ -2 \amp 5 \amp 4 \\ -5 \amp 6 \amp -3 \end{array} \right]

    This matrix has RREF,

        \left[\begin{array}{cc|c} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array} \right]

    Thus, the system is consistent with x_1 = 3, x_2 = 2, and so,

        3\vec{a}_1 + 2\vec{a}_2 = \vec{b}





    More generally, to solve a vector equation,



    x_1 \vec{a}_1 + \dots + x_n \vec{a}_n = \vec{b}




    Form the associated system of linear equations in x_1, \dots, x_n, and form its augmented matrix, whose columns will be \vec{a}_1, \dots, \vec{a}_n, \vec{b}. This is denoted by,



    \begin{bmatrix} \vec{a}_1 \amp \vec{a}_2 \amp \dots \amp \vec{a}_n \amp \vec{b} \end{bmatrix}




    Intuitively, this is a row vector with entries which are themselves column vectors, forming a matrix. Then, use row reduction to determine the solution. In summary,



    Vector equations as a linear system


        The vector equation,


        x_1 \vec{a}_1 + \dots + x_n \vec{a}_n = \vec{b}



        has the same solution set as the system of linear equations in x_1, \dots, x_n which has augmented matrix given by,


        \begin{bmatrix} \vec{a}_1 \amp \vec{a}_2 \amp \dots \amp \vec{a}_n \amp \vec{b} \end{bmatrix}



This provides an alternate interpretation of a linear system, in terms of vectors.


    Consider the linear system,

        \begin{array}{rrrr}
        x \amp + 3y \amp = -1 \\
        -5x \amp + 2y \amp = 2
        \end{array}

    which has vector form,

        x \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} + y \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}

    This equation can be thought of as trying to find a linear combination of the vectors (1, -5) and (3, 2) in the plane, that is equal to the vector (-1, 2).

Span of Vectors


    Let \vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n \in \mathbb{R}^n be vectors. The span of \vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n, denoted by \Span{\vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n}, is the set of all linear combinations of \vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n. In other words,

        \Span{\vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n} = \set{a_1 \vec{v}_1 + \dots a_n \vec{v}_n : a_1, \dots, a_n \in \mathbb{R}}





    By definition, a vector \vec{v} is in \Span{\vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n} if and only if \vec{v} can be written as a linear combination of \vec{v}_1, \dots, \vec{v}_n. From the previous result, this is true if and only if the linear system with augmented matrix,


    \begin{bmatrix} \vec{v}_1 \amp \dots \amp \vec{v}_n \amp \vec{v} \end{bmatrix}

has a solution.
